

-------------------


📘 Plain-language explanation of main.tf
Think of this Terraform file as a setup script for your AWS cloud environment. It creates the network, IAM permissions, an EKS cluster, worker nodes, and a few supporting AWS resources.

1. What this file is trying to build
This file creates:

a VPC (virtual private network)
public and private subnets
a NAT Gateway so private resources can reach the internet
route tables
a security group
IAM roles for EKS
an EKS cluster
an EKS node group (worker machines)
an EC2 instance with tools like kubectl and eksctl
EKS addons like CoreDNS, VPC CNI, kube-proxy, and pod identity agent
In short, it is preparing the AWS infrastructure needed to run your Kubernetes-based application.

2. The first part: Terraform provider setup
This section tells Terraform which AWS provider to use.

aws = "~> 5.0" means use AWS provider version 5.x
region = "us-east-1" means all resources will be created in the US East (N. Virginia) region
Simple meaning
Terraform needs to know which cloud provider and which region to work in.

3. The variable section

variable "cluster_version" {  default = "1.35"}
This defines a variable called cluster_version with a default value of 1.35.

Simple meaning
This is used to choose the Kubernetes version for your EKS cluster.
So if you later want Kubernetes 1.34 or 1.35, you can change it here.

4. The VPC section
aws_vpc.eks_vpc
This creates a VPC with CIDR block 10.0.0.0/16.

aws_internet_gateway.igw
This creates an Internet Gateway, which allows resources in the VPC to connect to the public internet.

Simple meaning
The VPC is the network boundary
The Internet Gateway is the door to the internet
5. The subnet section
This creates four subnets:

public1 and public2
private1 and private2
Public subnets
These are meant to be accessible from the internet.

map_public_ip_on_launch = true means EC2 instances launched here get a public IP automatically
Private subnets
These are internal subnets used for private resources.

Simple meaning
Public subnets = for resources that need internet access
Private subnets = for resources that should stay internal
6. NAT Gateway section
aws_eip.nat
Creates an Elastic IP, which is a static public IP.

aws_nat_gateway.nat
Creates a NAT Gateway in the public subnet.

Simple meaning
The NAT Gateway lets instances in private subnets access the internet without exposing them directly to the internet.

This is important because worker nodes in EKS often need to download packages or talk to external services, but you may not want them to have public IPs.

7. Route tables section
Public route table
This route table sends all outbound traffic (0.0.0.0/0) to the Internet Gateway.

Private route table
This route table sends all outbound traffic to the NAT Gateway.

Simple meaning
Public subnet resources can go directly to the internet
Private subnet resources go through NAT
The associations attach these route tables to the respective subnets.

8. Security group section
aws_security_group.allow_all
This creates a security group named allow-all-sg.

It allows:

all inbound traffic
all outbound traffic
Simple meaning
This security group is very open. It does not restrict traffic.

For a real production setup, this is usually not recommended. It is easier for testing, but not secure.

9. IAM roles section
Cluster role
This role allows the EKS control plane to manage the cluster.

It is attached to the AWS-managed policy:

AmazonEKSClusterPolicy
Worker role
This role is used by the EC2 worker nodes in the EKS node group.

It is attached to these policies:

AmazonEKSWorkerNodePolicy
AmazonEKS_CNI_Policy
AmazonEC2ContainerRegistryReadOnly
Simple meaning
These IAM roles are like permissions for AWS services.

The cluster role lets EKS manage the cluster
The worker role lets worker nodes join the cluster and pull container images
10. EKS cluster section
aws_eks_cluster.eks
This creates the EKS cluster.

Important settings:

name = naresh
Kubernetes version = var.cluster_version
VPC subnets = private1 and private2
endpoint_public_access = true
Simple meaning
This creates the Kubernetes control plane.

The cluster is placed in the private subnets, and its API endpoint is publicly accessible.

11. Node group section
aws_eks_node_group.node_group
This creates the worker nodes for the cluster.

Settings:

cluster name = naresh
node group name = eks-node-group
instance type = t3.medium
desired size = 4
min size = 1
max size = 6
subnets = private1 and private2
Simple meaning
This creates a group of EC2 machines that will run your Kubernetes pods.

The node group automatically scales between:

1 minimum
4 desired
6 maximum
So the cluster will try to keep 4 worker nodes running.

12. EC2 instance section
aws_instance.eks
This creates a separate EC2 instance in the public subnet.

It uses:

AMI = ami-02dfbd4ff395f2a1b
instance type = t2.medium
30 GB root volume
the same security group as above
User data
The user_data script installs:

kubectl
eksctl
Simple meaning
This EC2 instance is like a management machine.
It is used to interact with the EKS cluster and manage Kubernetes operations.

So the cluster itself is created in AWS, and this instance gives you a machine from which you can run Kubernetes commands.

13. EKS addons section
These are extra components installed on the cluster.

vpc-cni
This manages networking between pods and the AWS VPC.

coredns
This provides DNS service inside the cluster.

kube-proxy
This helps with network routing for services in Kubernetes.

eks-pod-identity-agent
This helps pods get AWS permissions securely.

Simple meaning
These are built-in Kubernetes components that make the cluster work properly.

14. EBS CSI role section
aws_iam_role.ebs_csi_role
This creates an IAM role named AmazonEKS_EBS_CSI_DriverRole.

It is intended for the EBS CSI driver, which is used to attach Amazon EBS volumes to Kubernetes pods.

Simple meaning
This role enables Kubernetes to use persistent storage.

15. What is not in this file
The database is created in a separate file: rds.tf

That file creates:

an RDS MySQL database
a DB subnet group
So the EKS infrastructure is in this file, and the database is in the other Terraform file.

16. A simple end-to-end view
Here is how the infrastructure works together:

Terraform creates a VPC and subnets
It sets up internet access for public subnets and NAT for private subnets
It creates IAM roles for EKS
It creates an EKS cluster
It creates worker nodes
It installs Kubernetes addons
It creates a management EC2 instance with kubectl and eksctl
The app can then be deployed into the cluster
17. Important beginner-friendly notes
✅ Good things in this file
It creates a complete EKS environment
It uses private subnets for the cluster and nodes
It creates a management instance for Kubernetes operations
⚠️ Things to be careful about
The security group is open to all traffic
The RDS configuration in rds.tf has a hardcoded password
The cluster endpoint is public
For production, you would usually improve security and use better secrets management
18. Short summary for a fresher
This Terraform file is basically saying:

“Create an AWS VPC, create public and private subnets, set up internet access, create IAM permissions, create an EKS cluster, create worker nodes, install Kubernetes addons, and create a helper EC2 machine so I can manage the cluster.”

If you want, I can also give you a visual architecture diagram of this setup or explain the file line by line in a very beginner-friendly way.


